00:50:34.720 --> 00:50:48.109
&gt;&gt;Person 1 from audience: So you know today
we think of compilers compiling into an assembly

00:50:48.109 --> 00:50:53.549
language which is some representation of the
underlying machine codes. Um, how did things

00:50:53.549 --> 00:50:57.730
look in the '50's to then, 'coz you haven't
mentioned the, you know, machine codes and

00:50:57.730 --> 00:51:02.519
assembly languages and things like that? And
also what was the correlation, if she had

00:51:02.519 --> 00:51:05.269
any, to John Backus who did the Fortran Compiler?

00:51:05.269 --> 00:51:14.239
&gt;&gt;Kurt: Sure, sure, yeah. Um, yeah there were
2 paths that were happening. Hoppers was the

00:51:14.239 --> 00:51:19.950
compiling path. Ah, there were other languages
growing, mainly out of MIT which were taking

00:51:19.950 --> 00:51:24.890
a different path. She was very friendly with
John Backus actually. When I talked about

00:51:24.890 --> 00:51:31.269
how she built this team that went beyond the
borders of UNIVAC, Backus was actually working

00:51:31.269 --> 00:51:42.519
at IBM. And one of the things that motivated
Backus was how slow MATH-MATIC compiled. So

00:51:42.519 --> 00:51:48.599
when he was designing what would become FORTRAN,
the main thing he was trying to solve was

00:51:48.599 --> 00:51:57.390
to figure out how to increase compiling speeds.
And so, very friendly with Hopper. Hopper,

00:51:57.390 --> 00:52:04.559
there were, software wasn't monetized at that
point so she had no problems working with

00:52:04.559 --> 00:52:08.170
him, making suggestions, they all knew each
other at the different conferences that they

00:52:08.170 --> 00:52:13.720
were going to. So it was a much different
time in terms of development back then.

00:52:13.720 --> 00:52:23.579
&gt;&gt;Person 2 from audience [European accent]:
I thought that was an interesting comment

00:52:23.579 --> 00:52:31.200
on Open Source in the early days. I think,
